------------------------------------------------------------------------
Third-Party Components
------------------------------------------------------------------------

This extension is a Postgres-extension artefact with two build flavours
under one source tree (`dist/tle/` for the pg_tle SQL-only build, and
`dist/pgrx/` for the pgrx-native Rust build). Its third-party surface
spans cryptographic reference implementations, test-vector corpora,
extension frameworks, and academic prior-art citations.

For the complete machine-readable list of dependencies actually shipped
with each release, see the project's SBOM (Software Bill of Materials)
generated for each release in CycloneDX 1.6 format and published
alongside the release artefacts on PGXN, dbdev, and (where applicable)
PostgreSQL APT/YUM repositories.

The following third-party components are anticipated for v0.1
(non-exhaustive; the SBOM published with each release is the
authoritative list):

  Cryptographic reference implementations:

    - Keccak Code Package (XKCP) — the canonical FIPS 202 reference
      implementation maintained by the Keccak design team
      (Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michaël Peeters, Gilles Van Assche,
      Ronny Van Keer). The TLE flavour's pure-plpgsql Keccak-f[1600]
      sponge construction is a clean-room port informed by the XKCP
      reference. Source: https://github.com/XKCP/XKCP and
      https://keccak.team. Licence: CC0 1.0 Universal public-domain
      dedication, with portions under a BSD-style licence; full licence
      text preserved in the upstream repository.

    - tiny_sha3 — a compact portable SHA-3 / Keccak reference by
      Markku-Juhani O. Saarinen. Used as a secondary reference for the
      TLE-flavour port to ensure correctness on small inputs and for
      cross-validation of the sponge state machine.
      Source: https://github.com/mjosaarinen/tiny_sha3.
      Licence: MIT.

  Test-vector corpora:

    - NIST CAVP Known Answer Test (KAT) corpus for FIPS 202 (SHA-3
      Standard). The full short-message and Monte Carlo KAT corpus is
      embedded in the extension and is verified by `pg_qsag.run_kats()`
      at extension installation time; loading is refused if any vector
      fails. Source: https://csrc.nist.gov/Projects/cryptographic-algorithm-validation-program/Secure-Hashing.
      Licence: US Government work; 17 USC §105 public domain in the
      United States; no copyright asserted internationally by NIST.

  PostgreSQL extension framework and core:

    - AWS pg_tle (Trusted Language Extensions for PostgreSQL) — the
      extension framework that enables the `dist/tle/` flavour to
      install on managed-Postgres tiers (RDS, Aurora, Supabase) where
      C extensions are forbidden. pg_qsag_audit's TLE flavour does not
      modify or redistribute pg_tle source; it is a consumer of the
      framework and assumes the framework is installed on the target
      database.
      Source: https://github.com/aws/pg_tle.
      Licence: Apache License 2.0.

    - PostgreSQL `pgcrypto` contrib module — the bundled hashing
      function set that pg_qsag_audit's `pg_qsag.digest()` dispatcher
      routes to when SHA3 is available via the OpenSSL EVP layer. We do
      not bundle or redistribute pgcrypto source; we depend on it being
      present in the target installation. Original authors: Marko Kreen
      (initial release) and the PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
      Source: https://github.com/postgres/postgres/tree/master/contrib/pgcrypto.
      Licence: PostgreSQL License (BSD-style with patent-grant clause).

  Build / development dependencies (anticipated for `dist/pgrx/`):

    - pgrx — the Rust-to-PostgreSQL extension framework
      (https://github.com/pgcentralfoundation/pgrx). Licence: Apache
      License 2.0 OR MIT (dual-licensed; pg_qsag_audit selects Apache
      2.0 for distribution consistency).

    - The Rust standard library and the `cargo` build toolchain.
      Licence: Apache License 2.0 OR MIT.

  Build / development dependencies (anticipated for `dist/tle/`):

    - PostgreSQL itself, version 14 or later, for plpgsql interpretation
      and the pg_tle framework.
      Licence: PostgreSQL License.

    - `pg_format` (or equivalent) for plpgsql formatting; `pgTAP` for
      test execution. These are development-time tools, not runtime
      dependencies of the shipped extension.

  Components anticipated for v0.5 (not present at v0.1):

    - liboqs (Open Quantum Safe) — for any ML-DSA / SLH-DSA / Falcon
      signatures emitted by the v0.5 SCITT Signed Statement emitter.
      Source: https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/liboqs.
      Licence: MIT.

    - RustCrypto crates (e.g. `sha3`, `hmac`, potentially `ml-dsa`) —
      for native pgrx hashing and signing primitives.
      Source: https://github.com/RustCrypto.
      Licence: Apache License 2.0 OR MIT.

Each component's full licence text is preserved in the dependency's own
distribution; we do not redistribute their source.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Academic Prior Art
------------------------------------------------------------------------

pg_qsag_audit's audit-chain primitive design draws on academic prior
art that is not a software dependency but is credited here per
scholarly convention:

  Madhwal, Yash; Yanovich, Yury; Anokhin, Ilya.
  "Blockchain Extension for PostgreSQL Data Storage."
  In Proceedings of the 3rd Blockchain and Internet of Things Conference
  (BIOTC 2021), pp. 24-30. ACM, July 2021.
  DOI: 10.1145/3475992.3476001

  Crosby, Scott A. and Wallach, Dan S.
  "Efficient Data Structures for Tamper-Evident Logging."
  In Proceedings of the 18th USENIX Security Symposium, pp. 317-334.
  USENIX Association, August 2009.
  Cited for the history-tree pattern adopted in the v0.5 Merkle
  accumulator design.

Where these works are referenced in the codebase or documentation, the
citation is preserved at the point of use; the works themselves are not
redistributed.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Standards Documents
------------------------------------------------------------------------

The following standards documents are referenced normatively or
informatively by pg_qsag_audit. Their text is not redistributed; they
are cited at the point of use:

    - NIST FIPS 202 — SHA-3 Standard.
    - NIST SP 800-185 — KMAC, TupleHash, ParallelHash.
    - NIST CSWP 39 — Crypto Agility (final 19 December 2025).
    - NIST SP 800-232 — Ascon (finalised 13 August 2025).
    - IETF RFC 8785 — JSON Canonicalisation Scheme (JCS).
    - IETF RFC 7515 — JSON Web Signature (JWS), used by PGXN v2 RFC-5
      Meta Spec v2 release certification.
    - IETF draft-ietf-scitt-architecture-22 — SCITT.
    - IETF draft-ietf-cose-merkle-tree-proofs-18 — COSE Receipts.
    - PGXN v2 RFC-2 (binary distribution), RFC-3 (Meta Spec v2),
      RFC-5 (JWS-signed META.json release certification).
    - EU Regulation 2024/1689 (AI Act), Article 12 and Article 26.
    - EU Regulation 2024/2847 (CRA), Article 14.
    - Contributor Covenant 2.1 (Code of Conduct text).

Standards documents published by NIST are US Government work and
public domain in the United States. IETF RFCs are subject to the
IETF Trust Legal Provisions (BCP 78 and BCP 79). EU Regulations are
published by the EU institutions under their own terms. PGXN v2 RFCs
are published under the PostgreSQL License or as public-domain
contributions to the PGXN Steering Committee. Contributor Covenant
2.1 is licensed CC BY 4.0.

